philosopher that we're going to read in this
course

00:00:38.640 --> 00:00:41.380
today we turn to Immanuel Kant

00:00:41.380 --> 00:00:44.850
who offers a different account

00:00:44.850 --> 00:00:47.840
of why we have a categorical duty

00:00:47.840 --> 00:00:50.870
to respect the dignity of persons

00:00:50.870 --> 00:00:52.539
and not to be use

00:00:52.539 --> 00:00:53.150
people

00:00:53.150 --> 00:00:55.180
as means

00:00:55.180 --> 00:00:58.520
merely

00:00:58.520 --> 00:01:01.360
even for good ends.

00:01:01.360 --> 00:01:03.520
Kant excelled at the university of Königsberg

00:01:03.520 --> 00:01:06.200
at the age of sixteen

00:01:06.200 --> 00:01:09.760
at the age of thirty one he got his first job

00:01:09.760 --> 00:01:12.340
as an unsalaried lecturer

00:01:12.340 --> 00:01:14.180
paid on commission

00:01:14.180 --> 00:01:17.720
based on the number of students who showed
up at his lectures

00:01:17.720 --> 00:01:20.920
this is a sensible system that Harvard would
do well to consider

00:01:30.189 --> 00:01:31.840
luckily for Kant

00:01:31.840 --> 00:01:37.450
he was a popular lecturer and also an industrious
one and so he eked out a meager living

00:01:37.450 --> 00:01:39.400
it wasn't until 

00:01:39.400 --> 00:01:42.530
he was fifty seven that he published his first

00:01:42.530 --> 00:01:44.750
major work

00:01:44.750 --> 00:01:46.549
but it was worth the wait

00:01:46.549 --> 00:01:49.229
the book was the critique of pure reason

00:01:49.229 --> 00:01:52.840
perhaps the most important work in all of
modern philosophy

00:01:52.840 --> 00:01:55.049
and a few years later

00:01:55.049 --> 00:01:55.920
Kant wrote

00:01:55.920 --> 00:02:02.080
the groundwork for the metaphysics of morals
which we read in this course

00:02:02.080 --> 00:02:05.540
I want to acknowledge even before we start

00:02:05.540 --> 00:02:08.020
that Kant is a difficult thinker

00:02:08.020 --> 00:02:10.989
but it's important to try to figure out

00:02:10.989 --> 00:02:14.459
what he's saying

00:02:14.459 --> 00:02:21.459
because what this book is about

00:02:21.489 --> 00:02:24.629
is well, it's about what the supreme principle of
morality this

00:02:24.629 --> 00:02:25.729
number one, and

00:02:25.729 --> 00:02:27.949
it's also

00:02:27.949 --> 00:02:29.889
it gives us an account

00:02:29.889 --> 00:02:32.030
one of the most powerful accounts we have

00:02:32.030 --> 00:02:34.249
of what freedom really is

00:02:34.249 --> 00:02:35.169
so

00:02:35.169 --> 00:02:38.019
let me start today.

00:02:38.019 --> 00:02:41.779
Kant rejects utilitarianism

00:02:41.779 --> 00:02:44.319
he thinks

00:02:44.319 --> 00:02:47.399
that

00:02:47.399 --> 00:02:49.169
the individual

00:02:49.169 --> 00:02:50.859
person

00:02:50.859 --> 00:02:54.349
all human beings

00:02:54.349 --> 00:02:57.419
have a certain dignity

00:02:57.419 --> 00:03:01.549
that commands our respect

00:03:01.549 --> 00:03:07.459
the reason the individual is sacred or the
bearer of rights according to Kant,

00:03:07.459 --> 00:03:12.209
doesn't stem from the idea that we own ourselves,

00:03:12.209 --> 00:03:15.090
but instead from the idea

00:03:15.090 --> 00:03:21.409
that we are all rational beings

00:03:21.409 --> 00:03:24.859
we're all rational beings which simply means

00:03:24.859 --> 00:03:27.849
that we are beings who are capable

00:03:27.849 --> 00:03:31.379
of reason.

00:03:31.379 --> 00:03:33.260
we're also

00:03:33.260 --> 00:03:36.619
autonomous beings

00:03:36.619 --> 00:03:38.019
which is to say

00:03:38.019 --> 00:03:42.319
that we are beings capable of acting and
choosing

00:03:42.319 --> 00:03:45.519
freely

00:03:45.519 --> 00:03:49.040
now, this capacity for reason and freedom

00:03:49.040 --> 00:03:52.259
isn't the only capacity we have.

00:03:52.259 --> 00:03:55.549
we also have the capacity for pain and
pleasure

00:03:55.549 --> 00:04:00.019
for suffering and satisfaction

00:04:00.019 --> 00:04:02.749
Kant admits the

00:04:02.749 --> 00:04:06.439
utilitarians were half a right

00:04:06.439 --> 00:04:09.430
of course

00:04:09.430 --> 00:04:12.299
we seek to avoid pain

00:04:12.299 --> 00:04:15.889
and we like pleasure

00:04:15.889 --> 00:04:18.539
Kant doesn't deny this

00:04:18.539 --> 00:04:21.349
what he does deny

00:04:21.349 --> 00:04:23.360
is Bentham's claim that

00:04:23.360 --> 00:04:25.560
pain in pleasure

00:04:25.560 --> 00:04:27.710
are our sovereign masters

00:04:27.710 --> 00:04:32.659
he thinks that's wrong.

00:04:32.659 --> 00:04:34.199
Kant thinks

00:04:34.199 --> 00:04:37.330
that it's are national capacity

00:04:37.330 --> 00:04:41.230
that makes us distinctive, that makes us special
that sets us

00:04:41.230 --> 00:04:43.860
apart from and above mere animal

00:04:43.860 --> 00:04:47.479
existence. 

00:04:47.479 --> 00:04:51.430
it makes us something more than just physical

00:04:51.430 --> 00:04:56.089
creatures with appetites. Now

00:04:56.089 --> 00:04:58.650
we often think

00:04:58.650 --> 00:05:00.499
of freedom

00:05:00.499 --> 00:05:02.699
as simply consisting

00:05:02.699 --> 00:05:06.620
in doing what we want

00:05:06.620 --> 00:05:10.340
or in the absence of obstacles to getting
what we want

00:05:10.340 --> 00:05:13.649
that's one way of thinking about freedom.

00:05:13.649 --> 00:05:15.939
but this isn't Kant's

00:05:15.939 --> 00:05:18.220
idea of freedom

00:05:18.220 --> 00:05:20.759
Kant has a more stringent

00:05:20.759 --> 00:05:21.879
demanding notion

00:05:21.879 --> 00:05:24.049
of what it means to be free

00:05:24.049 --> 00:05:28.079
and though stringent and demanding, if you think it  
through

00:05:28.079 --> 00:05:32.259
it's actually pretty persuasive

00:05:32.259 --> 00:05:34.659
Kant’s reason is as follows

00:05:34.659 --> 00:05:35.590
when we,

00:05:35.590 --> 00:05:37.389
like animals

00:05:37.389 --> 00:05:39.229
seek after pleasure

00:05:39.229 --> 00:05:43.189
or the satisfaction of our desires of the
avoidance pain

00:05:43.189 --> 00:05:49.180
when we do that we aren't really acting
freely.

00:05:49.180 --> 00:05:51.389
why not?

00:05:51.389 --> 00:05:53.609
we're really acting

00:05:53.609 --> 00:05:55.879
as the slaves 

00:05:55.879 --> 00:05:58.229
of those appetites

00:05:58.229 --> 00:06:00.580
and impulses

00:06:00.580 --> 00:06:06.189
I didn't choose this particular hunger or
that particular appetite,

00:06:06.189 --> 00:06:10.509
and so when I act to satisfy it

00:06:10.509 --> 00:06:13.430
I'm just acting according to natural

00:06:13.430 --> 00:06:15.110
necessity

00:06:15.110 --> 00:06:16.850
and for Kant,

00:06:16.850 --> 00:06:19.009
freedom is the opposite

00:06:19.009 --> 00:06:23.199
of necessity

00:06:23.199 --> 00:06:26.569
there was an advertising slogan

00:06:26.569 --> 00:06:27.430
for the

00:06:27.430 --> 00:06:28.789
soft drink Sprite

00:06:28.789 --> 00:06:31.680
a few years ago

00:06:31.680 --> 00:06:33.259
the slogan was

00:06:33.259 --> 00:06:37.990
obey your thirst

00:06:37.990 --> 00:06:39.259
there

00:06:39.259 --> 00:06:41.169
there's a Kantian insight

00:06:41.169 --> 00:06:42.210
buried in that

00:06:42.210 --> 00:06:45.160
Sprite advertising slogan

00:06:45.160 --> 00:06:46.800
that in a way is Kant's point

00:06:46.800 --> 00:06:48.720
when you go for Sprite,

00:06:48.720 --> 00:06:51.269
or Pepsi

00:06:51.269 --> 00:06:52.759
you're really

00:06:52.759 --> 00:06:56.619
you might think that you're choosing freely
sprite versus Pepsi

00:06:56.619 --> 00:06:58.479
but you're actually

00:06:58.479 --> 00:06:59.860
obeying

00:06:59.860 --> 00:07:05.939
something, a thirst, or maybe a desire manufactured
or massaged by advertising

00:07:05.939 --> 00:07:08.400
you're obeying a prompting

00:07:08.400 --> 00:07:10.199
that you yourself

00:07:10.199 --> 00:07:11.349
haven't chosen

00:07:11.349 --> 00:07:15.159
or created

00:07:15.159 --> 00:07:16.649
and here

00:07:16.649 --> 00:07:19.349
it's worth

00:07:19.349 --> 00:07:20.330
noticing

00:07:20.330 --> 00:07:23.009
Kant’s specially demanding

00:07:23.009 --> 00:07:23.729
idea

00:07:23.729 --> 00:07:24.669
of freedom

00:07:24.669 --> 00:07:27.240
what way

00:07:27.240 --> 00:07:31.000
of acting, how can my will be determined if not
by

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:37.460
the prompting sub nature or my hunger or my
appetite, or my desires?

00:07:37.460 --> 00:07:38.490
Kant's answer:

00:07:38.490 --> 00:07:40.550
to act freely

00:07:40.550 --> 00:07:42.259
is to act

00:07:42.259 --> 00:07:43.939
autonomously

00:07:43.939 --> 00:07:45.880
and to act autonomously

00:07:45.880 --> 00:07:49.219
is to act according to a law that I give
myself

00:07:49.219 --> 00:07:51.169
not according

00:07:51.169 --> 00:07:53.439
to the physical laws of nature

00:07:53.439 --> 00:07:57.769
or to the laws of cause and effect

00:07:57.769 --> 00:07:59.119
which include my desire,

00:07:59.119 --> 00:08:01.179
to eat or to drink

00:08:01.179 --> 00:08:05.169
or to choose this

00:08:05.169 --> 00:08:07.669
food in a restaurant over that

00:08:07.669 --> 00:08:09.649
now what is the opposite

00:08:09.649 --> 00:08:11.669
what is the opposite

00:08:11.669 --> 00:08:16.650
of autonomy

00:08:16.650 --> 00:08:21.409
for Kant he invest a special term

00:08:21.409 --> 00:08:22.879
to describe

00:08:22.879 --> 00:08:25.909
the opposite of autonomy

00:08:25.909 --> 00:08:27.430
heteronomy

00:08:27.430 --> 00:08:30.240
is the opposite of autonomy

00:08:30.240 --> 00:08:31.840
when I act

00:08:31.840 --> 00:08:33.680
heteronomously

00:08:33.680 --> 00:08:35.990
I'm acting

00:08:35.990 --> 00:08:38.040
according to an inclination

00:08:38.040 --> 00:08:39.600
or a desire

00:08:39.600 --> 00:08:42.720
that I haven't chosen for myself

00:08:42.720 --> 00:08:46.710
so freedom is autonomy

00:08:46.710 --> 00:08:49.820
is this specially stringent

00:08:49.820 --> 00:08:50.960
idea

00:08:50.960 --> 00:08:55.080
that Kant insists on.

00:08:55.080 --> 00:08:58.520
now why is autonomy

00:08:58.520 --> 00:09:04.500
the opposite of the acting heteronomously or
according to the dictates of nature

00:09:04.500 --> 00:09:06.360
Kant’s point is that

00:09:06.360 --> 00:09:09.450
nature is governed by laws

00:09:09.450 --> 00:09:15.110
laws of cause and effect for example

00:09:15.110 --> 00:09:18.190
suppose you drop a billiard ball

00:09:18.190 --> 00:09:21.720
it falls to the ground

00:09:21.720 --> 00:09:25.890
we wouldn't say the billiard ball is acting
freely

00:09:25.890 --> 00:09:27.090
why not?

00:09:27.090 --> 00:09:29.690
it's acting according to the law of nature

00:09:29.690 --> 00:09:31.550
according to the laws

00:09:31.550 --> 00:09:32.900
of cause and effect

00:09:32.900 --> 00:09:35.230
the law of gravity

00:09:35.230 --> 00:09:38.269
and just as he has an unusually

00:09:38.269 --> 00:09:40.129
demanding and stringent

00:09:40.129 --> 00:09:41.390
conception of freedom,

00:09:41.390 --> 00:09:43.490
freedom as autonomy,

00:09:43.490 --> 00:09:45.250
he also 

00:09:45.250 --> 00:09:49.300
has a demanding conception

00:09:49.300 --> 00:09:51.030
of morality

00:09:51.030 --> 00:09:52.670
to act freely

00:09:52.670 --> 00:09:57.610
is not to choose the best means to a given
end

00:09:57.610 --> 00:10:03.670
it's to choose the end itself for its own sake

00:10:03.670 --> 00:10:06.920
and that's something

00:10:06.920 --> 00:10:09.610
that human beings can do

00:10:09.610 --> 00:10:13.830
and that billiard balls can’t

00:10:13.830 --> 00:10:16.030
insofar as we act on

00:10:16.030 --> 00:10:17.920
inclination or pursue pleasure

00:10:17.920 --> 00:10:20.460
we fact as means

00:10:20.460 --> 00:10:22.480
to the realization of ends

00:10:22.480 --> 00:10:24.800
given outside us

00:10:24.800 --> 00:10:26.900
we are instruments

00:10:26.900 --> 00:10:29.010
rather than authors

00:10:29.010 --> 00:10:30.230
of the purposes

00:10:30.230 --> 00:10:32.550
we pursue

00:10:32.550 --> 00:10:34.130
that's

00:10:34.130 --> 00:10:37.600
the heteronomous determination of the
will

00:10:37.600 --> 00:10:38.899
on the other hand

00:10:38.899 --> 00:10:40.880
insofar as we act autonomously

00:10:40.880 --> 00:10:43.480
according to law we give ourselves

00:10:43.480 --> 00:10:45.659
we do something for its own sake

00:10:45.659 --> 00:10:47.880
as an end in itself

00:10:47.880 --> 00:10:49.720
when we act autonomously

00:10:49.720 --> 00:10:52.350
we cease to be instruments to purposes

00:10:52.350 --> 00:10:53.970
given outside us

00:10:53.970 --> 00:10:55.890
we become

00:10:55.890 --> 00:11:00.080
what we can come to think of ourselves

00:11:00.080 --> 00:11:03.070
as ends in ourselves.

00:11:03.070 --> 00:11:06.610
this capacity to act freely

00:11:06.610 --> 00:11:07.850
Kant tells us

00:11:07.850 --> 00:11:10.309
is what gives human life its special

00:11:10.309 --> 00:11:11.880
dignity.

00:11:11.880 --> 00:11:14.790
respecting human dignity

00:11:14.790 --> 00:11:16.119
means regarding persons

00:11:16.119 --> 00:11:18.280
not just as means

00:11:18.280 --> 00:11:21.600
but also as ends in them

00:11:21.600 --> 00:11:22.769
and this is why

00:11:22.769 --> 00:11:25.270
it's wrong to use people

00:11:25.270 --> 00:11:27.790
for the sake of other people's

00:11:27.790 --> 00:11:31.250
well being or happiness

00:11:31.250 --> 00:11:33.750
this is the real reason Kant says

00:11:33.750 --> 00:11:37.600
that utilitarianism goes wrong

00:11:37.600 --> 00:11:41.940
this is the reason it's important to respect
the dignity of persons

00:11:41.940 --> 00:11:46.390
and to uphold their rights.

00:11:46.390 --> 00:11:48.310
so even if there are cases

00:11:48.310 --> 00:11:52.370
remember John Stuart Mill said well in the
long run if we uphold Justice and respect

00:11:52.370 --> 00:11:54.790
the dignity of persons

00:11:54.790 --> 00:11:57.990
we will maximize human happiness.

00:11:57.990 --> 00:12:01.250
What would Kant's answer be to that?

00:12:01.250 --> 00:12:03.050
what would his answer be?

00:12:03.050 --> 00:12:05.150
even if that were true

00:12:05.150 --> 00:12:09.220
even if the calculus worked out that way

00:12:09.220 --> 00:12:13.579
even if you shouldn't throw the Christians
to the lions because in the long run

00:12:13.579 --> 00:12:17.850
fear will spread, the overall utility will decline, the
utilitarian

00:12:17.850 --> 00:12:22.150
would be upholding Justice and rights and
respect for persons

00:12:22.150 --> 00:12:25.160
for the wrong reason

00:12:25.160 --> 00:12:28.790
for a purely contingent reason

00:12:28.790 --> 00:12:31.620
for an instrumental reason

00:12:31.620 --> 00:12:36.210
it would still be using people even where the
calculus works out

00:12:36.210 --> 00:12:39.720
for the best in the long run, it would still
using people

00:12:39.720 --> 00:12:44.570
as means

00:12:44.570 --> 00:12:46.190
rather than

00:12:46.190 --> 00:12:50.990
respecting them as ends in themselves.

00:12:50.990 --> 00:12:54.420
so that's Kant's idea of freedom as autonomy

00:12:54.420 --> 00:12:57.390
and you can begin to see how it's connected

00:12:57.390 --> 00:13:01.430
to his idea of morality

00:13:01.430 --> 00:13:04.460
but we still have to answer one more question

00:13:04.460 --> 00:13:07.520
what gives an act it's moral worth

00:13:07.520 --> 00:13:09.310
in the first place

00:13:09.310 --> 00:13:12.160
if it can't be directed

00:13:12.160 --> 00:13:15.230
at utility or satisfying wants or desires, 

00:13:15.230 --> 00:13:19.870
what do you think gives an action it's moral worth?

00:13:19.870 --> 00:13:21.839
this leads us from Kant’s

00:13:21.839 --> 00:13:23.690
demanding idea of freedom

00:13:23.690 --> 00:13:25.830
to his demanding idea

00:13:25.830 --> 00:13:28.770
of morality.

00:13:28.770 --> 00:13:30.620
What does Kant say?

00:13:30.620 --> 00:13:33.580
what makes and action

00:13:33.580 --> 00:13:36.370
morally worthy

00:13:36.370 --> 00:13:41.350
consists not in the consequences or in the
results that flow from it

00:13:41.350 --> 00:13:46.030
what makes an action morally worthy has to do with

00:13:46.030 --> 00:13:48.360
the motive

00:13:48.360 --> 00:13:50.720
with the quality of the will

00:13:50.720 --> 00:13:53.820
with the intention

00:13:53.820 --> 00:13:56.480
for which the act is down

00:13:56.480 --> 00:13:57.770
what matters

00:13:57.770 --> 00:13:59.540
is the motive

00:13:59.540 --> 00:14:06.080
and the motive must be of a certain kind.

00:14:06.080 --> 00:14:10.330
so the moral worth of an action depends on the
motive for which it's done

00:14:10.330 --> 00:14:12.210
and the important thing

00:14:12.210 --> 00:14:13.390
is that

00:14:13.390 --> 00:14:15.820
the person do the right thing

00:14:15.820 --> 00:14:18.570
for the right reason

00:14:18.570 --> 00:14:21.110
a goodwill isn't good

00:14:21.110 --> 00:14:24.480
because of what it affects or accomplishes,
Kant writes,

00:14:24.480 --> 00:14:27.380
it's good in itself

00:14:27.380 --> 00:14:32.080
even if by its utmost effort to goodwill accomplishes
nothing

00:14:32.080 --> 00:14:35.610
it would still shine like a jewel for its own
sake

00:14:35.610 --> 00:14:38.980
as something which has its full value in itself

00:14:38.980 --> 00:14:41.250
and so for any action

00:14:41.250 --> 00:14:44.420
to be morally good

00:14:44.420 --> 00:14:46.009
it's not enough that it should

00:14:46.009 --> 00:14:47.320
conform

00:14:47.320 --> 00:14:49.010
to the moral law

00:14:49.010 --> 00:14:53.770
it must also be done for the sake of the moral
law.

00:14:53.770 --> 00:14:55.139
the idea is

00:14:55.139 --> 00:14:57.550
that the motive confers

00:14:57.550 --> 00:14:58.489
the moral worth

00:14:58.489 --> 00:15:00.650
on an action

00:15:00.650 --> 00:15:03.060
and the only kind of motive

00:15:03.060 --> 00:15:05.190
that can confirm moral

00:15:05.190 --> 00:15:06.720
worth on an action

00:15:06.720 --> 00:15:09.580
is the motive of duty

00:15:09.580 --> 00:15:11.610
well what's the opposite

00:15:11.610 --> 00:15:15.950
of doing something out of a sense of duty
because it's right,

00:15:15.950 --> 00:15:18.240
well for Kant the opposite

00:15:18.240 --> 00:15:23.330
would be all of those motives having to do
with our inclinations

00:15:23.330 --> 00:15:24.970
and inclinations

00:15:24.970 --> 00:15:26.720
refer to all of our

00:15:26.720 --> 00:15:29.779
desires, all of our contingently given

00:15:29.779 --> 00:15:30.850
wants

00:15:30.850 --> 00:15:31.290
preferences

00:15:31.290 --> 00:15:32.500
impulses

00:15:32.500 --> 00:15:34.490
and the like

00:15:34.490 --> 00:15:37.130
