00:46:46.429 --> 00:46:47.999
but suppose

00:46:47.999 --> 00:46:49.509
there was something

00:46:49.509 --> 00:46:51.349
whose existence

00:46:51.349 --> 00:46:52.709
has in itself

00:46:52.709 --> 00:46:54.699
and absolute value

00:46:54.699 --> 00:46:57.259
an end in itself

00:46:57.259 --> 00:46:59.640
then in it

00:46:59.640 --> 00:47:01.269
and in it alone

00:47:01.269 --> 00:47:06.450
would there be the ground of a possible a
categorical imperative

00:47:06.450 --> 00:47:09.019
well, what is there

00:47:09.019 --> 00:47:15.389
that we can think of as having it's end in
itself

00:47:15.389 --> 00:47:16.779
Kant’s answer is this

00:47:16.779 --> 00:47:18.739
I say that man

00:47:18.739 --> 00:47:21.909
and in general every rational being

00:47:21.909 --> 00:47:24.420
exists as an end in himself

00:47:24.420 --> 00:47:27.749
not nearly as a means for arbitrary use

00:47:27.749 --> 00:47:30.699
by this or that will

00:47:30.699 --> 00:47:32.869
and here Kant distinguishes

00:47:32.869 --> 00:47:35.069
between persons on the one hand

00:47:35.069 --> 00:47:36.279
and things

00:47:36.279 --> 00:47:38.069
on the other

00:47:38.069 --> 00:47:40.709
rational beings are persons

00:47:40.709 --> 00:47:42.979
the don't just have a relative value

00:47:42.979 --> 00:47:45.009
for us

00:47:45.009 --> 00:47:48.099
but if anything has they have an absolute
value

00:47:48.099 --> 00:47:50.059
an intrinsic value

00:47:50.059 --> 00:47:51.269
that is

00:47:51.269 --> 00:47:53.769
rational beings have dignity

00:47:53.769 --> 00:47:56.349
they're worthy of reverence and respect

00:47:56.349 --> 00:47:58.479
this line of reasoning

00:47:58.479 --> 00:48:04.439
leads Kant to the second formulation of the
categorical imperative which is this

00:48:04.439 --> 00:48:06.180
act in such a way

00:48:06.180 --> 00:48:08.909
that you always treated humanity

00:48:08.909 --> 00:48:11.019
whether in your own person

00:48:11.019 --> 00:48:13.949
or in the person of any other

00:48:13.949 --> 00:48:16.289
never simply as a means

00:48:16.289 --> 00:48:17.469
but always

00:48:17.469 --> 00:48:19.329
at the same time

00:48:19.329 --> 00:48:21.189
as an end

00:48:21.189 --> 00:48:24.910
so that's the formula of humanity

00:48:24.910 --> 00:48:27.219
as an end

00:48:27.219 --> 00:48:30.659
the idea that human beings as rational beings

00:48:30.659 --> 00:48:33.299
are ends in themselves

00:48:33.299 --> 00:48:36.209
not open to use

00:48:36.209 --> 00:48:38.749
merely as a means

00:48:38.749 --> 00:48:42.229
when I make a false promise to you

00:48:42.229 --> 00:48:46.549
I mean using you as a means

00:48:46.549 --> 00:48:48.389
to my ends

00:48:48.389 --> 00:48:51.160
to my desire for the hundred dollars

00:48:51.160 --> 00:48:55.269
and so I'm failing to respect

00:48:55.269 --> 00:48:58.699
you, I'm failing to respect your dignity

00:48:58.699 --> 00:49:01.189
I'm manipulating you

00:49:01.189 --> 00:49:03.319
now consider the example

00:49:03.319 --> 00:49:05.689
of the duty of against

00:49:05.689 --> 00:49:09.119
suicide

00:49:09.119 --> 00:49:09.969
murder

00:49:09.969 --> 00:49:12.179
and suicide

00:49:12.179 --> 00:49:17.469
are at odds with the categorical imperative
why?

00:49:17.469 --> 00:49:19.670
if I murdered someone

00:49:19.670 --> 00:49:23.739
I'm taking their life for some

00:49:23.739 --> 00:49:26.229
purpose. either because

00:49:26.229 --> 00:49:28.149
I'm a hired killer

00:49:28.149 --> 00:49:31.829
or I'm in the throws of some great anger
or passion

00:49:31.829 --> 00:49:34.549
well I have some interest or purpose

00:49:34.549 --> 00:49:35.880
that is particular

00:49:35.880 --> 00:49:38.599
for the sake of which I'm using them

00:49:38.599 --> 00:49:40.149
as a means

00:49:40.149 --> 00:49:42.329
murder violates

00:49:42.329 --> 00:49:46.089
the categorical imperative

00:49:46.089 --> 00:49:48.499
for Kant, morally speaking

00:49:48.499 --> 00:49:50.949
suicide is on a par with murder

00:49:50.949 --> 00:49:55.759
it's on a par with murder because what we
violate

00:49:55.759 --> 00:49:57.519
when we take a life

00:49:57.519 --> 00:50:02.029
when we take someone's life our's or somebody
else's

00:50:02.029 --> 00:50:04.199
we use that person

00:50:04.199 --> 00:50:05.950
we use a rational being

00:50:05.950 --> 00:50:09.779
we use humanity as a means

00:50:09.779 --> 00:50:12.500
and so we fail to respect humanity

00:50:12.500 --> 00:50:14.349
as an end

00:50:14.349 --> 00:50:16.470
and that capacity for reasons

00:50:16.470 --> 00:50:18.389
that humanity

00:50:18.389 --> 00:50:21.099
that commands respect

00:50:21.099 --> 00:50:23.719
that is to ground of dignity

00:50:23.719 --> 00:50:25.019
that humanity

00:50:25.019 --> 00:50:28.699
that capacity for a reason

00:50:28.699 --> 00:50:30.660
resides undifferentiated

00:50:30.660 --> 00:50:32.159
in all of us

00:50:32.159 --> 00:50:35.299
and so I violate that dignity

00:50:35.299 --> 00:50:38.710
in my own person if I commit suicide

00:50:38.710 --> 00:50:39.689
and in murder

00:50:39.689 --> 00:50:43.489
if I take somebody else's life from a moral
point of view

00:50:43.489 --> 00:50:45.309
they're the same

00:50:45.309 --> 00:50:47.969
and the reason they're the same

00:50:47.969 --> 00:50:49.069
has to do

00:50:49.069 --> 00:50:51.789
with the universal character

00:50:51.789 --> 00:50:53.229
and ground

00:50:53.229 --> 00:50:56.389
of the moral law

00:50:56.389 --> 00:50:58.739
the reason that we have to respect

00:50:58.739 --> 00:51:01.150
the dignity of other people

00:51:01.150 --> 00:51:02.290
has not to do

00:51:02.290 --> 00:51:03.349
with anything

00:51:03.349 --> 00:51:06.189
in particular about them

00:51:06.189 --> 00:51:12.289
and so respect, Kantian respect is
unlike love in this way

00:51:12.289 --> 00:51:14.749
it's unlike sympathy

00:51:14.749 --> 00:51:20.049
it's unlike solidarity or fellow feeling
for altruism

00:51:20.049 --> 00:51:25.329
because love and those other particular virtues
are reasons for caring about other people

00:51:25.329 --> 00:51:28.359
have to do with who they are in particular

00:51:28.359 --> 00:51:30.380
but respect for Kant

00:51:30.380 --> 00:51:31.819
respect

00:51:31.819 --> 00:51:34.009
is respect for 

00:51:34.009 --> 00:51:36.059
humanity which is universal

00:51:36.059 --> 00:51:38.919
for a rational capacity which is universal

00:51:38.919 --> 00:51:41.159
and that's why violating it

00:51:41.159 --> 00:51:42.700
in my own case

00:51:42.700 --> 00:51:44.519
is as objectionable

00:51:44.519 --> 00:51:45.570
as violating it

00:51:45.570 --> 00:51:48.190
in the case of any other

00:51:48.190 --> 00:51:55.190
questions or rejections?

00:51:58.129 --> 00:52:01.849
I guess I'm somewhat worried about

00:52:01.849 --> 00:52:04.549
Kant’s

00:52:04.549 --> 00:52:08.619
statement that you cannot use a person
as a means because every person is an end

00:52:08.619 --> 00:52:10.699
in and of themselves

00:52:10.699 --> 00:52:13.229
because it seems that

00:52:13.229 --> 00:52:16.409
that everyday in order to get something accomplished
for that day

00:52:16.409 --> 00:52:20.559
I must use myself as a means to some end

00:52:20.559 --> 00:52:24.489
and I must use the people around me as a means
to some ends as well

00:52:24.489 --> 00:52:25.859
for instance suppose

00:52:25.859 --> 00:52:28.379
that

00:52:28.379 --> 00:52:31.609
I want to do well in a class and I have to write a
paper

00:52:31.609 --> 00:52:34.949
I have to use myself as a means to write the paper

00:52:34.949 --> 00:52:38.399
suppose I want to buy something, food.

00:52:38.399 --> 00:52:41.160
I must go to the store, use the person

00:52:41.160 --> 00:52:45.599
working behind the counters as a means for me to  
purchase my food.

00:52:45.599 --> 00:52:47.909
You're right, that's true

00:52:47.909 --> 00:52:49.849
what's your name? Patrick

00:52:49.849 --> 00:52:52.839
Patrick you're not doing anything wrong

00:52:52.839 --> 00:52:55.629
you're not violating the categorical imperative

00:52:55.629 --> 00:52:58.130
when you use other people as a means

00:52:58.130 --> 00:53:03.089
that's not objectionable provided

00:53:03.089 --> 00:53:08.409
when we deal with other people for the sake
of advancing our projects and purposes and

00:53:08.409 --> 00:53:09.049
interests,

00:53:09.049 --> 00:53:11.569
which we all do,

00:53:11.569 --> 00:53:12.329
provided

00:53:12.329 --> 00:53:13.579
we treat them

00:53:13.579 --> 00:53:14.660
in a way

00:53:14.660 --> 00:53:16.690
that is consistent

00:53:16.690 --> 00:53:18.609
with respect for their

00:53:18.609 --> 00:53:20.759
dignity

00:53:20.759 --> 00:53:24.180
and what it means to respect them

00:53:24.180 --> 00:53:26.119
is given by

00:53:26.119 --> 00:53:31.880
the categorical imperative.

00:53:31.880 --> 00:53:34.129
are you persuaded?

00:53:34.129 --> 00:53:38.549
do you think that Kant has given

00:53:38.549 --> 00:53:41.499
a compelling account a persuasive account

00:53:41.499 --> 00:53:48.410
of the supreme principle of morality?

00:53:48.410 --> 00:53:50.899
re-read the groundwork

00:53:50.899 --> 00:53:57.899
and we'll try to answer that question next
time.

